First, let's find the symmetric difference of A and B (AΔB). The symmetric difference is the set of elements which are in either of the sets, but not in their intersection.

A = {1, 2, 3}
B = {2, 3, 4}

Intersection of A and B (A∩B) = {2, 3}

AΔB = (A - A∩B) ∪ (B - A∩B) = ({1, 2, 3} - {2, 3}) ∪ ({2, 3, 4} - {2, 3}) = {1} ∪ {4} = {1, 4}

Now, let's find the symmetric difference of (AΔB) and C.

(AΔB) = {1, 4}
C = {3, 4, 5}

Intersection of (AΔB) and C ((AΔB)∩C) = {4}

(AΔB)ΔC = ((AΔB) - (AΔB)∩C) ∪ (C - (AΔB)∩C) = ({1, 4} - {4}) ∪ ({3, 4, 5} - {4}) = {1} ∪ {3, 5} = {1, 3, 5}

Finally, let's find the union of the resulting set with the set D.

(AΔB)ΔC = {1, 3, 5}
D = {1, 3, 5}

Union of (AΔB)ΔC and D ((AΔB)ΔC ∪ D) = {1, 3, 5}

So the final result is {1, 3, 5}.
